Returning to the very American ideal of labor rights as human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have introduced legislation to make union organizing a civil right.
"As unions die, so do middle-class jobs," said Ellison, a Minnesota Democrat and vice chairman of the Congressional Progressive Caucus.
So I proudly introduce the Employee Empowerment Act alongside civil rights icon John Lewis.
This landmark law gives workers the same legal remedies against discrimination for union organization as against other forms of discrimination - putting a stop to anti-union forces.
Amending the national Labor Law Act to provide a way for workers who have faced discrimination to organize union representation to seek justice in civil court - and obtain compensation or fines - is a worthwhile and necessary initiative.
But it's certainly not a radical initiative - at least not by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis and the other sponsors of their bill are proposing is to tie it back to a very American idea.
Despite the setbacks unions have faced in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states across the country - Americans have once encouraged countries around the world to recognize, expand and uphold labor rights.
There was a time, millions of Americans still remember, when this country mentioned democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to organize in the same breath.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his staff encouraged the country to adopt a constitution designed to ensure that the militarized autocracy of Hedki Tojo would be replaced by democracy.
Fully aware of the role workers and their unions had in the creation of a new Japan, they used language that explicitly recognized that "the rights of workers to organize and collective bargaining and action are guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his staff urged the Germans to write a constitution that would see the fascism of Adolf Hitler replaced with a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would need to organize and raise their voices in the new nation, the Germans included a clause that stated explicitly: "The right to form associations to improve working and economic conditions securing and improving is guaranteed to every individual and every profession or trade.
Agreements that restrict or aim to reduce this right are null and void; measures aimed at this are unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt presided over the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, as adopted by the United Nations as a worldwide convention in 1948, Roosevelt and the other drafters included a guarantee that " Everyone has the right to form or join trade unions to protect his interests."
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
As that country advised other countries on how to form civil and democratic societies, Americans declared that the right to form a union -- and then have that union participate in collective bargaining as an equal partner with corporations and government agencies -- should be protected must.
Indeed, with these rights coming under attack in America, it is very wise to revisit the American ideal that working people must have the right to unite and have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As Pastor Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the labor movement did not limit the strength of the nation but increased it.
By raising the living standards of millions of people, work has miraculously created a market for industry and raised the entire nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack the work forget these simple truths, but history preserves them.
History remembers, and so should we.
The formal recognition of labor rights as human rights - and the extension of civil rights protections to protect against discrimination in the creation of workers' representation - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis renew the ideals that made America great in the past and delivered on the promise of democracy.
