Charity CMT UK said misdiagnosis is a common problem for people with CMT because so little is known about the disease.
Around 23,000 people in the UK are believed to have CMT, which can lead to motor disorders such as muscle weakness, an unsteady gait and crooked toes.
Patients also experience numbness or pain. The disease is incurable and progressive, meaning symptoms get worse over time.
When Rodgers was 13, she believed she had Friedreich's Ataxia (FA) - a disease with a very poor chance of survival.
Rodgers thought she would be in a wheelchair before she was 18 and die before her 30th birthday.
The mother-of-two, who is now 51, said: "As a child I knew I couldn't do the same as everyone else.
I kept falling and everything took longer for me.
I never got to roller skate or skateboard with the other kids and was often teased at school for the way I walked and ran.
Rodgers said that at age 13, after multiple surgeries to relieve her Achilles tendons and straighten her feet, she was looking at her medical records when her doctor left the room and read that she had FA.
"I felt guilty because I was curious, so I didn't tell anyone, but I went home, looked up the disease in the library and wrote to the FA Society," she said.
When I got the answer, I was shocked and panicked terribly.
I thought I would be in a wheelchair by 18 and die by 25, slowly losing all my abilities in between.
I sorted it all out on my own and planned my own funeral.
She said when she turned 17 she realized her abilities hadn't diminished as much as she had imagined and consulted her doctor.
