Washington area business tax burden rises with economic recovery
A recovery in the economy means more customers, more sales and new jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
State and local corporate tax bills in the country rose modestly last year as the economic recovery accelerated, according to a newly released study last week, and Washington-area firms were no exception.
Companies in the District, Maryland and Virginia area collectively paid $27.6 billion to state and local government agencies in fiscal 2013, a 3.8 percent increase from 2012 revenues of $26.6 billion.
The state and local corporate tax burden rose 4.3 percent last year to $671 billion, compared to 3.9 percent a year earlier, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after several years of falling assessments in 2009 and 2010 .
State taxes rose more than local taxes, by 4.3 percent, according to the study, conducted by services agency Ernst & Young with the Center for State Taxation, a tax policy group.
More than half of the district's tax revenue, 56 percent, comes from corporate taxes, while 36 percent of Maryland's revenue comes from corporations.
Virginia has the lowest corporate tax revenue at 28 percent.
Much of the rise in tax revenue is due to a rebound in corporate property values, the researchers say, leading to a 3.7 percent increase in property taxes this year after three consecutive years of growth rates of less than 1 percent.
While a large portion of these wins came from big states like California, New York and Texas, the pattern seems to apply to the Washington area as well.
Businesses in the District, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid more than $10 billion in state and local real estate taxes last year, compared to $9.6 billion in 2012 -- a 4.2 percent increase over the year.
But the apparent recovery in real estate values isn't as effective in increasing state and local tax revenues in Maryland, where real estate taxes account for just over one-fifth of corporate tax bills.
Virginia and D.C. businesses pay almost half of their state and local taxes in real estate taxes.
"What's happening in Maryland is that a large portion of real estate, particularly in the D.C. tax jurisdiction, is owned either by the government or by non-profit organizations that don't pay real estate taxes," said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the Center on State Taxation.
Maryland, for example, is forced to rely much more on income taxes to provide the same services that other states provide.
The recent rebound in corporate tax revenues cannot be attributed solely to the rebound in the real estate market
Corporate earnings also appear to be recovering, according to the data.
Businesses in the region reported income taxes at state organizations of $2.3 billion compared to $2.1 billion in 2012.
Maryland raked in $1 billion in corporate income taxes, the region's highest.
While trending in the same direction, the local corporate tax burden is not increasing equally in all three locations.
The District's increase rate of 4.3 percent was in line with the national average, while Maryland's increase was significantly higher, at 4.9 percent.
Only Virginia reported below-average tax revenue of 4.1 percent.
Virginia has by far the lowest corporate income taxes in all three jurisdictions (all three have fixed corporate tax rates) at 6 percent.
The corporate tax rate in Maryland is 8.25 percent and the District is a relatively high 9.975 percent.
A similar study by the US Chamber of Commerce earlier this year showed that Virginia has lower state and local corporate taxes and an overall better tax climate than Maryland.
The district was not examined in the study.
Despite the advantages, Virginia is under pressure from its southern neighbor.
North Carolina passed legislation to lower its corporate tax rates from 6.9 percent to 6 percent this year, the same rate as Virginia, and the rate will drop to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to meet its income targets next year, this law could reduce the state's corporate income tax rate to as low as 3 percent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small businesses in the Washington area appear to be doing better and paying more state and local taxes as a result, according to the latest study.
Corporate taxes, which are paid as personal income taxes by small business owners -- a transitional structure under which most small businesses are organized -- in the District, Maryland and Virginia rose 20 percent to $2.4 billion last year, a significantly faster growth rate than the total corporate taxes.
The researchers say the trend and increase in corporate taxes across the country is likely to continue this year, with general sales tax receipts for the state and local governments increasing 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year same period of the previous year.
Still, the Washington area could lag behind if the federal government's spending cut affects jobs in the region.
